            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old woman with a rounded, slightly overweight build (BMI ~28.4) who presents to her primary care physician for a routine annual check-up. She appears well-groomed and professionally dressed, reflecting her role as a senior marketing manager at a mid-sized retail company. She reports feeling generally well but admits to occasional fatigue and mild shortness of breath when climbing stairs, symptoms she had attributed to her busy schedule and stress. Her skin tone is slightly flushed, and there are no visible xanthomas or xanthelasmas, though a faint arcus cornealis is noted on ophthalmic inspection.\n\n{patientName} leads a predominantly sedentary lifestyle, spending 8–10 hours a day at a desk and commuting by car. She enjoys cooking — particularly Italian and Southern cuisine — and tends to favor meals rich in saturated fats and simple carbohydrates. She rarely exercises, with the last structured physical activity being a yoga class she attended \"a few months ago.\" She drinks one to two glasses of red wine most evenings and has a remote smoking history of approximately 5 pack-years, having quit at age 38.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys reading historical fiction, gardening on weekends, and spending time with her two adult children who live nearby. She is divorced and lives alone in a suburban home. She has a close group of friends with whom she socializes regularly, often at restaurants. She describes her stress level as \"chronically high\" due to workplace deadlines and some ongoing financial concerns.\n\n{patientName} denies chest pain at rest, palpitations, or syncopal episodes. She reports menopausal symptoms over the past two years — notably hot flashes and disrupted sleep — which she manages with lifestyle measures alone. She has not previously been screened for cardiovascular risk in a formal sense, and this is the first time a lipid panel has been ordered for her."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f7603c38-fd87-42f5-accd-2d39f3aabf43",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a medical history notable for mild hypertension diagnosed three years ago, currently managed with lifestyle modification with intermittent adherence. She entered menopause approximately two years ago and has declined hormone replacement therapy. She has no prior diagnosis of diabetes mellitus, though a fasting glucose of 101 mg/dL was noted on a workplace health screening two years ago, raising concern for pre-diabetes. She has no documented history of cardiovascular disease, stroke, or peripheral arterial disease.\n\n{patientName} has no prior hospitalizations. She underwent a laparoscopic cholecystectomy for symptomatic cholelithiasis in 2017 and had a caesarean section with her second child in 1999. She has a remote smoking history (quit age 38, ~5 pack-years). Alcohol consumption is approximately 7–10 units per week. She takes no regular prescription medications at this time, though she occasionally uses ibuprofen for tension headaches and takes over-the-counter vitamin D supplements.\n\nFamily history is significant for coronary artery disease in her father and hypercholesterolaemia in her mother, both of whom were diagnosed in their 50s. Her paternal grandfather died of a myocardial infarction at age 62. These factors, combined with her postmenopausal status and lifestyle profile, place her in a moderate-to-high cardiovascular risk category. A formal cardiovascular risk score (e.g., SCORE2) should be calculated to guide treatment intensity."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
